                    "company": "Stage Director  -  freelance",
                    "description": "During the 70\u2019s, 80\u2019s and 90\u2019s directed, amongst dozens of productions, the European premieres of both A.R. Gurney\u2019s \"Love Letters\u201d and Eric Bogosian\u2019s \u201cSex, Drugs, Rock & Roll\u201d.  Also at the helm of the critically acclaimed production of William Hanley\u2019s \u201cSlow Dance on the Killing Ground\u201d as well as numerous other sold-out productions including Edward Albee\u2019s \"American Dream\", A.R. Gurney\u2019s \"Love Letters\", Bernard Shaw\u2019s \u201cThe Philanthropist\u201d, Noel Coward\u2019s \u201cPrivate Lives\u201d and 3 different stage versions of Samuel Beckett\u2019s \u201cWaiting for Godot\u201d.  In 1985 directed the Dutch subsidized English language production of G.A. Bredero's \u201cThe Spanish Brabanter\u201d (\u201cDe Spaanschen Brabander\u201d) in the Amsterdam Stadsschouwburg on the occasion of celebrating the 400th anniversary of the author\u2019s birth with several performances of his most celebrated comedy.\n\n\nStageography  (selective list) -   \nSex, Drugs, Rock & Roll by Eric Bogosian\nMary Stuart by Dacia Maraini\nLove Letters by A.R. Gurney\nThe Woolgatherer by William Mastrosimone\nPrivate Lives by Noel Coward \nLoot by Joe Orton\nThe Spanish Brabanter by G.A. Bredero \nThe Philanderer by George Bernard Shaw\nFaith Healer by Brian Friel\nSlow Dance On The Killing Ground by William Hanley \nWaiting for Godot (3 separate productions) by Samuel Beckett\nThe Woods by David Mamet\nThe Philanthropist by Christopher Hampton\nWho's Afraid of Virginia Woolf? by Edward Albee\nCamera Obscura by Robert Patrick \nThe Golden Fleece by A.R. Gurney\nThis is the Rill Speaking by Lanford Wilson\nAmerican Dream by Edward Albee  \nMurphy's Mental Chamber based upon the novel \"Murphy\" by Samuel Beckett \nHome Free by Lanford Wilson \nMr. Foot by Michael Frayn\nAll On Her Own by Terence Rattigan \nThe Conquest of Everest by Arthur Kopit\nLudlow Fair by Lanford Wilson\nThe Applicant by Harold Pinter \nWandering by Lanford Wilson \nAuto-da-f\u00e9 by Tennessee Williams\nI Rise in Flame, Cried the Phoenix by Tennessee Williams",
